Que: when to choose ThreadPoolTaskExecutor and ExecutorService.
Choose ThreadPoolTaskExecutor if you are working within a Spring Boot or Spring Framework application. It makes configuration cleaner, manages the bean lifecycle 
automatically, and natively drives annotations like @Async.
@Bean
public Executor asyncExecutor() {
   ThreadPoolTaskExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolTaskExecutor();
   executor.setCorePoolSize(1000);
   executor.setMaxPoolSize(1000);
   executor.setQueueCapacity(1000);
   executor.setThreadNamePrefix("Async-");
   executor.initialize();
   return executor;
}
Choose ExecutorService if you are developing a lightweight, standalone Java application or building a core Java library that should not depend on external frameworks like Spring.

ExecutorService :
The ExecutorService in Java is a framework provided by the java.util.concurrent package that simplifies asynchronous task execution by automatically managing a pool of 
threads. Instead of manually instantiating new Thread() for every task, you submit tasks to the ExecutorService, which reuses existing worker threads to optimize performance.
